# DeerTheGreat — Command Cheat Sheet

## Basic syntax
```bash
python3 main.py <target> [options]
```
Run this from inside the `~/deerthegreat` folder (or use the `deerthegreat` command if you set up the symlink).

---

## Target formats (required, first argument)

| Format | Example | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| Single IP | `python3 main.py 192.168.1.1` | Scans one address |
| Hostname | `python3 main.py example.com` | Resolves the domain to an IP, then scans it |
| CIDR subnet | `python3 main.py 192.168.1.0/24` | Scans every host in that subnet (254 addresses) |
| IP range | `python3 main.py 192.168.1.1-50` | Scans .1 through .50 |
| Comma list | `python3 main.py 192.168.1.1,192.168.1.5,10.0.0.1` | Scans exactly those hosts |

---

## Flags

### `-p, --ports` — which ports to scan
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -p 80              # just port 80
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -p 22,80,443       # a specific list
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -p 1-1000          # a range
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -p top100          # default — 100 most common ports
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -p all             # every port, 1–65535 (slow)
```

### `-c, --concurrency` — how many connections run at once (default 500)
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.0/24 -c 1000   # faster, more aggressive
python3 main.py 192.168.1.0/24 -c 100    # gentler, less likely to trip anything
```

### `-t, --timeout` — seconds to wait per connection attempt (default 1.0)
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -t 0.5   # faster scan, may miss slow-to-respond ports
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -t 3     # slower but more reliable on laggy networks
```

### `--no-banner-grab` — skip reading service banners (faster, less info)
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.0/24 -p all --no-banner-grab
```

### `-o, --output` — save results to a JSON file
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 -o results.json
cat results.json
```

### `--no-ui` — plain text, no colors/animation (good for logging or piping)
```bash
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1 --no-ui >> scan_log.txt
```

---

## Combined examples

```bash
# Quick scan of your whole home network, common ports only
python3 main.py 192.168.1.0/24

# Fast, aggressive full-port scan of one machine
python3 main.py 192.168.1.50 -p all -c 1000 -t 0.5

# Careful, thorough scan — save to file
python3 main.py 10.0.0.5 -p all -t 2 -o full_scan.json

# Check if a web/ssh server is reachable
python3 main.py mywebsite.com -p 22,80,443

# Scan a range quietly, log to a file for later review
python3 main.py 192.168.1.1-100 --no-ui -o range_scan.json
```

