## Finding your own network range
```bash
ip a
```
Look for your local IP (e.g. `192.168.1.42`) — your subnet is everything before the last number, e.g. `192.168.1.0/24`.

---

## Responsible use
Only scan networks/hosts you own or have explicit permission to test. Random IPs on the internet are not fair game — that can cause real legal trouble even if unintentional. Your own home network, personal devices, or boxes you control are all fine.
